---
import SiteLayout from "../../../../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";
import Breadcrumbs from "../../../../../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Why PoliceConduct.org Documents Positive Police Conduct Too"
  description="A draft article explaining why PoliceConduct.org documents commendable police conduct alongside misconduct reports as part of a fuller accountability record."
  pagePath="/news/2026/03/29/why-policeconduct-org-documents-positive-police-conduct-too/"
>
  <main class="">
    <section class="py-vh-3 bg-gray-100 border-bottom border-dark">
      <div class="container">
        <Breadcrumbs
          items={[
            { label: "News", href: "/news/" },
            {
              label: "Why Positive Conduct Matters",
              href: "/news/2026/03/29/why-policeconduct-org-documents-positive-police-conduct-too/",
              current: true,
            },
          ]}
        />
        <div class="row">
          <div class="col-12 col-lg-10">
            <p class="text-uppercase small text-muted mb-2">Coming Soon</p>
            <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold">
              Why PoliceConduct.org Documents Positive Police Conduct Too
            </h1>
            <p class="lead text-muted mb-0">
              <strong>Dover, Delaware — March 29, 2026</strong> — PoliceConduct.org
              is preparing a public explanation of why the project documents commendations
              and respectful police interactions alongside misconduct reports.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="py-vh-2">
      <div class="container">
        <p>
          Police accountability should not mean pretending every officer is the
          same. A credible public record should make harmful conduct easier to
          see, but it should also preserve examples of restraint, fairness,
          professionalism, and de-escalation.
        </p>
        <p>
          This upcoming article will explain why documenting positive conduct is
          consistent with the project&apos;s mission and why that distinction
          matters for the public, for agencies, and for officers who serve
          honorably.
        </p>

        <h2 class="h4 text-uppercase text-muted mt-5">Planned Topics</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Why credibility requires more than a one-sided record</li>
          <li>How positive examples help identify good policing practices</li>
          <li>Why recognition and accountability can coexist</li>
          <li>How commendations can strengthen trust in the platform</li>
          <li>Why the project is pro good policing, not pro misconduct</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</SiteLayout>
